 Entities (1482); Relationships (2178)].\"},{\"summary\":\"HF is the primary worked example: fluorine draws electron density, leaving hydrogen partially positive\",\"explanation\":\"Hydrogen fluoride (HF) is used to illustrate bond polarization and polar covalent bonding: because fluorine is more electronegative than hydrogen, electron density shifts toward fluorine, creating partial charges while the molecule remains overall neutral [Data: Entities (1476, 627, 1481, 1482)].\\n\\nA specific relationship states that HF contains hydrogen bearing a partial positive charge due to electron displacement toward fluorine, directly grounding the δ+ assignment on hydrogen in HF [Data: Relationships (2154); Entities (1476, 1482)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Non-polar covalent bonds are defined by similar/equal electronegativities and symmetric electron sharing; H2 exemplifies this\",\"explanation\":\"A non-polar covalent bond is defined as having symmetric electron distribution between atoms with equal or similar electronegativities; this is linked directly to the electronegativity concept as the criterion for non-polar classification [Data: Entities (1478, 750); Relationships (2152)].\\n\\nHydrogen molecule (H2) is described as two hydrogen atoms sharing electrons to form a single covalent bond, and a relationship specifies that this bond features equal electronegativity (consistent with non-polar sharing) [Data: Entities (1437, 1478); Relationships (2153)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Homoatomic molecules (H2 and F2) anchor the ‘equal atoms → symmetric bonding’ principle, with F2 explicitly described as covalent sharing\",\"explanation\":\"H2 is described as a homoatomic molecule formed when two hydrogen atoms share electrons to create a single covalent bond, supporting the broader community theme that identical atoms share electrons evenly [Data: Entities (1437); Relationships (2153)].\\n\\nSimilarly, fluorine is described as forming F2 when two fluorine atoms share a pair of electrons, and t